Fertile, however, as these principles might have been in a different age, it must be consessed that they bore little fruit in the time oi which I am speaking. It was only men of rare curiosity or os a singular love oi nature, like Albert the Great⁷ or our own Roget Bacon, who saw the supreme importance oi interrogating facts or ot ¹ basing science upon experience. To the latter oi these great names ι’ l shall devote some little space.

First, however, 1 may remark, by way os parenthesis, that Dr. Whewell⁸ discovers certain resemblances between the mediaeval mystic Richard os St. Victor (died 1¹7 3) and Francis Bacon. Oi these, the most important is the dictum that ‘Physical science ascends from effects to causes, and descends again from causes to effects⁹.' This, however, appears to me to be one of those incidental utterances which might easily be made without perceiving‚ as Bacon undoubtedly did perceive, its scientific value or the practical con· sequences to which, if properly developed, it would lead.

The comparison os the speculations oi Roger Bacon (who wrote towards the end ofthe thirteenth century) with those os his namesake are specially interesting, and have been made much oi by those who deny or depreciate the originality of the latter ¹⁰. The whole spirit oi his works bears, perhaps, a nearer resemblance to those oi Francis Bacon than can be found in any intermediate writer, but here, oi course, I must confine myseli to specilic points and to a few typical quotations.
